0.   Introduction

 

In this Lab you connect watsonx Orchestrate using open-source solutions

 

A short video introduction of the use case for this lab is here:

 

https://youtu.be/JxjfAQh8ii0

 

The three open-source solutions used in the demo are:

 

         BAMOE to run the decision service.

See https://www.ibm.com/products/business-automation-manager-open-editions

 

         Cloudant to store ticket data.

See https://www.ibm.com/products/cloudant

 

         React to create the ticket report.

See https://react.dev/

 

The Lab is structured into the following sections.

 

         Build a speeding ticket decision service.

 

         Build a skill to save the ticket to a database.

 

         Build a skill flow to combine the above and create a report.

0.1 Pre-requisites

To perform this Lab, you need:

 

         Microsoft Remote Desktop (RDP)

         A GitHub Account. See https://github.com

         An IBM watsonx Orchestrate Standard account with Builder role.

         Techzone BAMOE VM : https://techzone.ibm.com/my/reservations/create/64a7121eb9776b0016a10cb0

 

Alternatively, you can build your own environment, in which case you need:

         VSC and the IBM BAMOE plugin

         Git Bash

         Latest Java JDK

 

1.   Build a decision service to calculate speeding fines

 

In this task, you ...

         Import a speeding ticket decision service.

         Run the service locally.

         Expose the decision service to the outside world

 

1.1 Before you start

 

In this exercise, you will build and test the decision service using Visual Studio Code (VSC).

 

1. Find the following BAMOE Techzone image (or later version if available):

 

https://techzone.ibm.com/collection/ibm-business-automation-manager-open-editions-environment/environments

 

IMPORTANT! When reserving, ensure VPN Access address is enabled. This is required to invoke API calls into the VM:

2. Once the VM is reserved, login with Remote Desktop (RDP). On Windows this is:

 

User: .\techzone

Password: IBMDem0s!

 

For further details see the getting started guide here: https://ibm.box.com/v/IBM-BAMOE-ENV

 

After login, you can switch the language locale in the image so that your keyboard is mapped correctly.

 

1.      Open Git Bash by clicking the Git Bash icon on the Windows Taskbar at the bottom of the screen.

 

2.      Within the Git Bash shell, clone the rule project using the command:

 

git clone https://github.com/ncrowther/bamoe2wxo

 

3.    Hit return. You should see the git repository cloned into the local drive:

 

Now open the decision project with VSC:

 

cd bamoe2wxo/

code SpeedingDecisionService/

 

4.      VSC will open:

5.      On the left-hand side of Visual Studio Code in file explorer locate src\main\resources\TrafficViolation.dmn

6.      Click the DMN file to view it:

7.    On the far right, select the properties icon . In the DMN Model Name, prepend the name with your initials. For example, if your initials are XXX, the DMN Model name would be XXXTrafficViolation:

8.    Select the Fine decision and edit it by selecting

9.    You should see the decision table below:

This decision table will be used later in the lab to calculate speeding fines depending on severity.

 

10.           Press Save (CTRL S).

1.2 Run the Decision Service

 

In this step we are going to convert the decision model into a callable decision service. We will

run our decision service in development mode using Quarkus. For details on Quarkus, visit https://quarkus.io/

 

0.      Within the VSC editor, click on the Terminal menu at the top of the screen:

 

1.      In the drop down click on New Terminal.



2.      In this terminal window, verify you are in the SpeedingDecisionService folder and then run Maven build:

 

mvn quarkus:dev

 

3.     Once built, our decision model is deployed to Quarkus and ready to run. Take note of the URL encircled below. This is the development URL:

 

1.3 Expose the decision service

 

1.      Within the VSC editor, click the PORTS tab. If you dont see this option, you must update VSC. To do this, select Help->Restart to update. In this case, you will have to run the mvn quarkus:dev command again in the terminal.

2.      Select Forward a Port.

 

3.      Enter kogito service port 8123 as the Port and hit return. You will see the following:

4.      Select Allow and enter your GitHub credentials.

 

5.      If successful, you should be returned to VSC and see this:

6.      Right-click Private in the Visibility column and change Port Visibility from Private to Public:

7.      Press Continue to accept the warning message. Select the copy local address button to store the exposed URL into your clipboard.


1.4 Test the Decision Service

 

Lets look at the API generated by Quarkus.

 

1.     Open a browser. This can be any browser anywhere in the world as your Decision Service is public.

 

2.      Paste the following URL into the browser address and press Enter.

 

[REMOTE_URL]/q/swagger-ui

 

Where [REMOTE_URL] is the URL you copied in the last step of the previous section. Accept the warning by pressing Continue. You should see this:

You are looking at the decision service endpoints exposed to the internet. If you followed the instructions, your endpoints have your initials prepended. You should see three endpoints, but the only endpoint we are interested in is POST /XXXTrafficViolation.

 

3.      Click on the POST /XXXTrafficViolation endpoint to expand it, then click the Try it out button on the right-side.

4.      Enter data into the request body:

 

{

"Violation": {

"Date": "2023-12-21",

"SpeedLimit": 20,

"ActualSpeed": 40

},

"DriverId": "D45454"

}

 

5.  Press Execute. You should see the following in the server response:

Response Body

{
 "Violation": {
 "SpeedLimit": 20,
 "ActualSpeed": 40,
 "Date": "2023-12-21"
 },
 "DriverId": "D45454",
 "Fine": {
 "Points": 3,
 "Amount": 500
 }

 

6.      Verify the points are 3 and the fine is 500.

 

7.      Congratulations, you have built and deployed the Speeding Ticket decision service on your local machine and exposed it to the outside world. The next step is to generate an OpenAPI specification to execute the service from watsonx Orchestrate.

 

2.     Generate an OpenAPI specification

 

In this section you generate an OpenAPI specification for watsonx Orchestrate.

 

Important! The decision service in the previous section must still be running in a separate VSC session.

 

1.      Reopen Git Bash shell.

 

2.      Within the Git Bash shell, open the OpenApiGenerator folder in VSC:

cd ~/bamoe2wxo

code OpenApiGenerator/

 

3.      Another VSC editor should appear:

4.      Expand the data folder and edit config.json. You should see this:

5.      Change the name of decisionId by replacing [YOUR_INITIALS] with your initials. This should be the same name as in section 7. For example, if your initials are XXX, the DMN Model name would be XXXTrafficViolation.

 

6.      Change localUrl to the local URL of your running Kogito service. If you are using the Techzone VM this should be already correct.

 

7.      Change the external URL to the one you stored in the clipboard on page 11.

 

8.      Save config.json using Ctrl-S .

 

9.      Open CreateOpenApi.java in the src/converter folder:

10. Right-click anywhere in the code and select Run Java. Accept the Windows Defender message if it appears. You should see this:

11. An open API file is generated. The generation is logged in the terminal of VSC:

If you see an error instead, check that your decision service is still running from section 1.2

 

12. Within VSC explorer, expand the /generated folder and click [YOUR_INITIALS]TrafficViolation.json.

 

13. Copy and paste (Ctrl-A, Ctrl-C, Ctrl-V) the entire file contents into https://editor.swagger.io, replacing the entire sample YAML on the left panel.

 

14. Press OK when you see a convert to YAML message:

15. You should see the same decision service we inspected in section 1.4.

16. There are differences compared with the original:

         Your initials have been appended.

         x-ibm annotations have been added.

         The data model has been pulled into the specification.

         Only one endpoint is generated.

Test this OpenAPI, following the same steps specified in section 1.4. If successful, the Open API is ready for watsonx Orchestrate!

3.   Import the OpenAPI into watsonx Orchestrate

 

1.      Login to IBM watsonx Orchestrate: https://dl.watson-orchestrate.ibm.com

2.      Under Build -> Skills, select Add skills

3.      Select From files

4.      Drag the OpenAPI file below into the drop area:

 

~/bamoe2wxo/OpenApiGenerator/generated/[YOUR_INITIALS]TrafficViolation.json

 

TIP: If you are using a VM you need to perform this in two steps

1.      Drag the remote file to your local desktop.

2.      Drag the local file to the drop area.

5.      Click Next. Select the [YOUR_INITIALS]TrafficViolation skill and press Add.

6.      Find the [YOUR_INITIALS]TrafficViolation skill.

7.      Right click the button with three vertical dots, and select Enhance this skill:

 

8.      Publish the skill[1]:

 

 

9.      Click on Skills Catalog

 

10. Find the [YOUR_INITIALS]TrafficViolation skill (type in full to find it). Select it and press Add skill

11. On the top right of the screen click Connect app and enter any username and password (credentials are placebos).

 

12. Go to Chat and run the skill by typing [YOUR_INITIALS]trafficviolation

 

13. The Traffic Violation data form appears. Enter the following data:

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

14. Hit Apply. This invokes the decision service via your local PC using the exposed port.

 

15. The response should contain the following response fields:

 

Congratulations! You have run your first BAMOE Decision Service from IBM watsonx Orchestrate.

4.   Persist Decisions

 

In this section we call a database to store speeding tickets. We use a public instance.

 

1.      Reopen Git Bash shell

 

2.      Within the Git Bash shell, open the cloudantFacade in VSC. You should leave the other two VSC instances open.

 

cd ~/bamoe2wxo

code cloudantFacade/dataservice

 

3.      The VSC editor should appear with the cloudantFacade/Dataservice folder.

4.      Expand the openapi folder and edit dataApi.yaml

 

5.      Perform a global search and replace of the text [YOUR_INITIALS], replacing with your initials. To do this, select Ctrl-R

 

 

6.      Press for a global replace

 

7.      Save dataApi.yaml using Ctrl-S

 

8.      Paste the contents of dataApi.yaml into https://editor.swagger.io

 

9.      You should see the following, with your initials instead of XXX:

10. Now we will import this API into Orchestrate

 

11. Login to IBM watsonx Orchestrate

 

12. Under Build -> Skills, select Add skills and then From files. Then drag and drop the dataApi.yaml API spec:

13. Click Next. Select the first two skills and press Add.

14. Publish both skills and add them to your catalog, as described in section 3. When connecting, you can use any user and password.

 

15. You should now have both skills published under the cloudantWxoFacade and added to your catalog.

 

16. Go to Chat (Personal Skills). Run the skill [YOUR INITIALS] write a doc to cloudant. Enter a driverId starting with D and then six numbers, and a date following the format YYYY-MM-DD. Any other values are fine:

17. Hit Apply.

 

18. Now run the get docs from cloudant skill. You should see all speeding fines retrieved from the database.

19. Find your entry by using the search button:

 

Congratulations! You have run your first Cloudant skill by entering data and retrieving it from watsonx Orchestrate.

 

5.   Create a Composite Flow using Decisions, Cloudant and React

 

We will now combine the Decision skill and the Cloudant skill with a React UI.

 

1.      Under Build -> Skills, select the down arrow on the Add Skills button and choose Create a skill flow.

2.      You should see the following:

3.      Select the pen and name the flow [YOUR_INITIALS] IssueSpeedingTicket, where [YOUR_INITIALS] are your initials. Click the Save button.

 

4.      Select the symbol and add [YOUR_INITIALS]TrafficViolation. Your flow should look like this (where NTC should be your initials):

 

5.      Select the rightmost symbol and add [YOUR_INITIALS]write a doc to Cloudant. Your flow should look like this:

6.      Select [YOUR_INITIALS]write a doc to Cloudant.

7.      Select generate mapping suggestions.

8.      Slide the toggle Hide this form from the user. You should see this:

9.      At the very bottom of the form, enter Speeding as the violation by clicking on the pencil:

10. Select the rightmost symbol and add [YOUR_INITIALS]get docs from Cloudant. Your flow should now look like this:

 

 

 

11. Select the rightmost symbol and add Custom Forms->Input Form

 

12. Slide the toggle Hide this form from the user. You should see this:

 

13. Press the Add input field button and assign it a type of Single line text:

14. Press Next and give it a Display label of TicketURL. Press Apply. You should see this:

15. Select TicketURL and map it to driverId from get docs from Cloudant.

Important! This must be driverId from get docs from Cloudant and not write a doc to cloudant

16. In the Define Transformations section, enter the following data exactly as specified:

 

Operator:

Replace a string

Search for:

D

Replace with:

https://fineui.1apbmbk49s5e.eu-gb.codeengine.appdomain.cloud/?driverId=D

 

You should see this:

17. Select the rightmost symbol and add Custom Forms->Output Form.

 

18. Enter # in the output form and select Input form->TicketURL as the field:

19. Press OK. You should see this:

20. The completed skill flow should look as follows:

21. Press the drop-down next to Actions and then save as draft. Then enhance and publish the skill flow.

 

22. Add the skill to your catalog. Go to Build->Skills. In the Search skills text field, type the full name of the composite flow into the search bar of the Skill catalog [YOUR INITIALS]IssueSpeedingTicket. When found, your Skill flow is shown:

23. Click on your flow and press Add skill

 

24. In Chat, run the [YOUR_INITIALS]IssueSpeedingTicket skill.

 

25. Enter a speeding violation. Ensure your driver Id starts with a capital D, for example D123456:

26. Press Apply.

 

27. After a while you should all speeding violations. Search for your driver id using the search button . If you find more than one entry for the same driver id, select the topmost one:

28. Press Apply

 

29. You should see a Ticket URL displayed. Click the URL. The URL invokes a reporting tool with your specified driverID as a parameter. The tool fetches additional data from Cloudant using the driverID as the key, and then creates a ticket like the one below:

 

Congratulations! You have completed the lab!

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

6.   Conclusion

 

In this lab we imported two skills from IBM watsonx Orchestrate: a decision skill and a database skill. We then combined these two skills to create a speeding ticket report

 

Thank you for taking this lab and I hope you create new applications using this technology.

 

7.   Advanced Labs

 

In these advanced labs we implement the Cloudant and React skills used in the labs above. These labs are aimed at experienced developers.

 

 

8.   Advanced Lab 1 Create a Cloudant Speeding Ticket Service

 

8.1 Local host Prerequisites

 

1.      Create a Cloudant instance in your IBM Cloud account.  

2.      See: https://cloud.ibm.com/docs/Cloudant?topic=Cloudant-getting-started-with-cloudant

3.      Create a Cloudant instance with name wxodb.

4.      Create credentials.

8.2 Run on local host

 

5.      Clone repo: https://github.com/ncrowther/bamoe2wxo

6.      Go to folder: bamoe2wxo/cloudantFacade/dataservice

7.      Edit setenv.bat to your Cloudant credentials

8.      Open Command prompt (NOT powershell).  Enter:

 

   setenv.bat

 

 Install a local nodejs server:

 

npm install

 

 Start a local nodejs server:

 

npm start

 

If the port is in use, change the port on line 32:

 

bamoe2wxo/cloudantFacade/dataservice/app.js

 

A local instance of the Cloudant service should now be running.

 

Open the OpenAPI spec:

 

bamoe2wxo/cloudantFacade/dataservice/openapi/dataApi.yaml

 

Write a ticket with:

 

POST https://localhost:3000/doc

 

Read the tickets with:

 

GET https://localhost:3000/docs:

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

8.3 Code Engine Hosting Prerequisites

 

This section describes how you can host your Cloudant service on IBM Code Engine.

 

1.      Create a Code Engine instance in IBM Cloud account. If using TechZone, reserve the following:

2.      Login to the provisioned environment.

 

3.      Create a code engine project called cloudant-facade, with the image referencing your docker image.

1.      Within your CodeEngine project, select Secrets and configmaps. Press Create.

 

2.      Create a configmap with name dataserviceconfig and press Create.

 

3.      Create a code engine configmap configuration with your Cloudant credentials:

 

8.4 Deployment to Code Engine

 

1.      Open Git Bash shell from VSC

 

2.      Login to IBM Cloud.

 

ibmcloud login --sso

 

3.      In the IBM Cloud console, go to Manage > Account > Account resources > Resource groups. Select the resource group for Code Engine. E.g. default

 

ibmcloud target -g default

 

4.      Select the code engine project:

 

ibmcloud ce project select -n [PROJECT_NAME]

 

5.      Start Docker Desktop

 

6.      In Bash Shell, go to the dataservice folder e.g: /bamoe2wxo/cloudantFacade/dataservice

 

7.      Within this folder, edit build.sh and run.sh and change the REGISTRY to your Docker registry.

 

8.      Run build.sh to build the sample application in your docker repo:

 

./build

 

9.      Run run.sh to deploy the application to Code Engine on IBM Cloud:

 

./run

 

10. Open the Code Engine console and copy the Cloudant service URL.

 

11. Edit the openAPI spec

 

bamoe2wxo/cloudantFacade/dataservice/openapi/dataApi.yaml

 

12. Change the server URL so that it points to your Cloudant service URL

 

13. Import the dataApi.yaml as a skill in IBM Watson x orchestrate and run the skill.

 

 

9.   Advanced Lab 2 Create a Report in React

 

9.1 Run on local host

 

Clone repo: https://github.com/ncrowther/bamoe2wxo

Go to folder: bamoe2wxo/reactCloudant

 

Open Command prompt. Enter:

 

npm install

 

 Start a local nodejs server:

 

npm start

 

The React reporting tool should appear. Enter the following URL, supplying a driver id that exists in the Cloudant database:

 

http://localhost:[PORT]/?driverId=D123456

 

If successful, this should display a Speeding report like the one below:

 

9.2 Deployment to Code Engine

 

To deploy on Code Engine, follow the README instructions in

 

bamoe2wxo/reactCloudant/README.md
